Grades are awarded on a scale of 1 to 10, where a result of at least 5.5 represents a
pass. All grades should be rounded to one decimal. This has to be the nearest
decimal.
In order to complete a module successfully and obtain ECTS for the module, the final
grade must be at or above 5.50 before rounding off. Grades between 5.45 and 5.49
are therefore rounded down to a 5.4.
When no result can be assigned, the label ‘no grade’ (NG) is assigned. An NG will be
assigned when the examiner cannot assess the knowledge, understanding
and/or skills of the student as a result of for example fraud/plagiarism, absence at
the exam or an incomplete assessment.
ARTICLE 14: GRADE POINT AVERAGE (GPA)
1.
2.
3.
4.
The grade list attached to the diploma indicates the final grade point average (GPA)
to provide a reflection of the student’s academic performance.
The GPA is calculated on the basis of all assessments of modules a student passed
and that are registered in the student’s progress records and the certificate for the
final examination.
The GPA is calculated by dividing the “sum of weighted grades” by the “sum of
credits”. The sum of weighted grades is calculated by adding the overall
assessments for modules passed, multiplied by the credit value of these modules.
The sum of credits is calculated by adding the number of credits of the modules the
student has passed and thus received credits for.
Credits obtained through credit transfer are excluded from the GPA.
